"SYNOPSIS: Implement squashfs to create a compressed /usr image for a live "
"cd."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:14
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: This hint is a guide to creating a compressed /usr image as "
"/usr usually tends to be the larget directory on a system. The user is then "
"given a quick example of how to implement this on a Live CD by mounting the "
"image at boot time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:17
msgid "ATTACHMENTS: http://squashfs.sourceforge.net/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:21
msgid "PREREQUISITES: A complete LFS system The kernel source code"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:24
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:30
msgid ""
"Introduction To start with a full explanation of Squashfs can be found at "
"the following link: http://squashfs.sourceforge.net/ if you have trouble "
"undertanding this hint If you are short of space on your machine or would "
"like to create a live cd containing lots of software, this hint is ideal for "
"you"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t\t\t\tAcquiring Squashfs \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The source code can also be downloaded from this site\t\n"
"\t\t\t\thttp://squashfs.sourceforge.net/\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:40
msgid ""
"The package used in this hint is squashfs3.2-r2. The document located at "
"www.artemio.net/projects/linuxdoc/squashfs/SquashFS-HOWTO.html was refrenced "
"and adapted to the circumstance of the hint."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t\t\tPatching and recompiling the Kernel\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:46
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In order to use squashfs, the kernel needs to have a patch applied.Un pack "
"the source tar ball. \n"
"\ttar xvfz squashfs3.2-r2.tar.gz\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:50
msgid ""
"The patch can be found in /linux-2.6.16 of the source code directory. The "
"patch we require is called: linux-2.6.16.27-utf8_input-1.patch"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:52
msgid ""
"Move the patch to the directory the kernel source is located at. apply the "
"patch using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:54
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tpatch -Np1 -i ../linux-2.6.16.27-utf8_input-1.patch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:57
msgid ""
"The menu driven kernel configuration must then be initiated again and "
"squashfs must be selected within the supported file systems menu."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t\t\tCompiling mksquashfs\n"
"To compile the sourcecode, navigate to the /squashfs-tools directory within "
"the sourcecode \n"
"and type make. Following compilation, copy the executable file to a more "
"appropriate directory:\n"
"\tcp mksquashfs /usr/sbin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:66
msgid ""
"To check everything went accordingly, type mksquashfs and the help dialogue "
"associated with the command will be displayed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t\t\t\tUsing Squashfs\n"
"On our system, /usr is by far the biggest directory. The most simple and "
"logical approach \n"
"would be to compress this directory and then uncompress and mount during the "
"system boot. As /usr \n"
"is not needed early during this boot process and exists generally as a read "
"only directory this is \n"
"a safe procedure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:76
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A compressed file can be created using the following command from the top "
"level root directory:\n"
"\t\tmksquashfs /usr usr.sqsh\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:80
msgid ""
"Depending on how large the /usr directory is, this command can take a while "
"to execute so maybe go grab a cofee....  Once done, the resulting usr.sqsh "
"file can be copied to the Live CD partition. The /usr directory on the CD "
"must then be emptied:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t\trm-fr $LIVECD/usr/*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Finally create a small start-up script  in $LIVECD/etc/rc.d/init.d called "
"usr or something similar. \n"
" Insert the following text:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:87
msgid "#!/bin/bash"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t  \tmount /usr.sqsh /usr -o loop\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:91
msgid "Make the file executable. Next create a symbolic link:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t\tln ï¿½l $LIVECD/etc/rc.d/init.d/usr $LIVECD/etc/rc.d/rcsysinitt/S35usr\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:97
msgid ""
"This will trigger the kernel to mount the usr.sqsh image to the /usr "
"directory during the system boot process. Upon logging on, the /usr "
"directory will be fully populated and appear to be exactly as it was before "
"we compressed it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:100
msgid ""
"Thats all there is to it. Please feel free to contact me if you have an "
"alternative way of doing this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/squashfs.txt:102
msgid ""
"As a final comment, I implemented this on a CD using an initrd using this "
"procedure."
msgstr ""

